## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `ThreadAbortException` | **Never raised** — catch block is dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Removed** |
| Manual `Thread` + `volatile bool` | Use `CancellationToken` + `Task` / `BackgroundService` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;

public class BackgroundProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so GetNextItem can unblock on cancellation
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — replaces ThreadAbortException
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    // If GetNextItem is truly synchronous/blocking, wrap it:
    private async Task<WorkItem> GetNextItemAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        // Option A: If the API supports cancellation natively
        return await _queue.DequeueAsync(ct);

        // Option B: If wrapping a blocking call (last resort)
        // return await Task.Run(() => GetNextItem(ct), ct);
    }
}
```

### Registration (Program.cs)

```csharp
var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);
builder.Services.AddHostedService<BackgroundProcessor>();
var host = builder.Build();
host.Run();
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. `Thread.Abort()` silently breaks** — it compiles but throws at runtime:
```
System.PlatformNotSupportedException: Thread.Abort is not supported on this platform.
```
Your old `Stop()` method will crash instead of stopping the worker.

**2. `ThreadAbortException` catch is dead code** — no mechanism in .NET 8 raises it, so rollback never executes. Data corruption risk if you rely on it.

**3. Blocking calls ignore cancellation** — if `GetNextItem()` blocks on I/O or `Monitor.Wait`, setting `_running = false` won't unblock it. You must pass `CancellationToken` into the blocking call:
```csharp
// BAD: blocks forever despite cancellation
var item = _queue.Take();

// GOOD: throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
var item = await _channel.Reader.ReadAsync(ct);
```

**4. `Thread.Sleep` → `Task.Delay`** — `Thread.Sleep` blocks the thread pool. Use:
```csharp
await Task.Delay(2000, stoppingToken);
```

**5. Graceful shutdown timeout** — `BackgroundService` has a default 30s shutdown timeout. Configure if needed:
```csharp
builder.Services.Configure<HostOptions>(opts =>
    opts.ShutdownTimeout = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
```

**6. Replace `volatile bool` entirely** — `CancellationToken` is the idiomatic cooperative cancellation mechanism. It's thread-safe, composable, and integrates with async APIs. A `volatile bool` can't unblock a waiting call.

### If You Can't Use `BackgroundService`

Minimal standalone equivalent:

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _runningTask;

    public void Start() =>
        _runningTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoopAsync(_cts.Token));

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();
        if (_runningTask is not null)
            await _runningTask.WaitAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
    }

    public void Dispose() => _cts.Dispose();
}
```

The core lesson: **.NET 8 uses cooperative cancellation exclusively** — there is no way to forcibly abort a thread. Design all long-running work to observe `CancellationToken`.
